{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.69,0.01,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79040"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4260"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64392"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79040"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a one week history of increasing abdominal distension. He has been previously diagnosed with alcoholic liver disease. He is on a sodium-restricted diet, spironolactone 400 mg/day, and furosemide 160 mg/day. On examination, he is fully conscious, jaundiced and has tense ascites. His blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min, respiratory rate 28/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and SpO2 92% on room air. A chest X-ray shows basal atelectasis. A therapeutic paracentesis is planned to relieve his symptoms. He will require intravenous fluid replacement whilst this is being done.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following intravenous fluids would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["5% dextrose","0.9% Sodium chloride","Albumin","Dextran","Lactated Ringer\u2019s"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with known liver cirrhosis presents with tense ascites, dyspnoea, and hypoxaemia. The respiratory distress could be related to increased abdominal pressure and splinting of the diaphragm due to tense ascites. Large volume paracentesis (\u0026gt; 5 litres) is indicated in this tense ascites causing respiratory distress. This procedure may cause paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction (PICD). \u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended to prevent this abnormality (dose is 6\u20138 g per litre of ascitic fluid removed). Albumin is still superior to synthetic colloids (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Edextran\u003C/strong\u003E) in preventing PICD. Albumin, a plasma expander, helps maintain intravascular volume and prevents these complications by counteracting the reduction in effective arterial blood volume that can occur after fluid removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECrystalloids such as \u003Cstrong\u003E5% dextrose\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E0.9% sodium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Elactated Ringer\u2019s\u003C/strong\u003E are not suitable for replacement after large volume paracentesis as two-thirds of the infused volume will move into the tissues, only the remaining third will stay in the intravascular space. This makes them ineffective in maintaining circulatory stability in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction (PICD) is a harmful complication of large volume paracentesis that should be prevented by plasma expanders (albumin).","Albumin is the preferred intravenous fluid to prevent PICD after large volume paracentesis in patients with cirrhosis."],"references":["Aithal GP, Palaniyappan N, China L, H\u00e4rm\u00e4l\u00e4 S, Macken L, Ryan JM, Wilkes EA, Moore K, Leithead JA, Hayes PC, O\u0027Brien AJ, Verma S. Guidelines on the management of ascites in cirrhosis. Gut. 2021 Jan;70(1):9-29. doi: 10.1136/gutjnl-2020-321790. Epub 2020 Oct 16. PMID: 33067334; PMCID: PMC7788190. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33067334/","Alsebaey A, Rewisha E, Waked I. Paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction: are there albumin alternatives? Egyptian Liver Journal 2020;10:1\u20136. Available from: https://eglj.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s43066-020-00047-7","Facciorusso A, Nacchiero MC, Rosania R, Laonigro G, Longo N, Panella C, Ierardi E. The use of human albumin for the treatment of ascites in patients with liver cirrhosis: item of safety, facts, controversies and perspectives. Curr Drug Saf. 2011 Sep 1;6(4):267-74. doi: 10.2174/157488611798280906. PMID: 22129322. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22129322/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64392"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64392"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:45:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T13:45:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4260"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79040"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[